  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Diction is word choice — the selection of specific words from the available alternatives. Every word carries denotation (what it refers to), connotation (what it suggests), register (what social context it belongs to), and rhythm (how it sounds in the sentence). Diction is where meaning and style meet.\nThe difference between \u0026ldquo;house,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;home,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;dwelling,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;residence,\u0026rdquo; and \u0026ldquo;domicile\u0026rdquo; is diction. Each refers to roughly the same thing, but each carries different associations: \u0026ldquo;home\u0026rdquo; is warm and personal; \u0026ldquo;domicile\u0026rdquo; is legal and bureaucratic; \u0026ldquo;dwelling\u0026rdquo; is archaic or literary. A writer who reaches for \u0026ldquo;domicile\u0026rdquo; when they mean \u0026ldquo;home\u0026rdquo; is not being precise — they\u0026rsquo;re being pretentious. A writer who uses \u0026ldquo;home\u0026rdquo; in a legal document is not being clear — they\u0026rsquo;re being imprecise. Diction is the match between word, context, and purpose.\n",
